{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"a8eae519e9e6b089","x":-195,"y":-207,"width":595,"height":327,"type":"text","text":"lets not make a title first\nlets make the authentic writing first, then figure out a title later\n\ncause the authentic thing is that i am afraid that i am ripping people off by charging for something that i wish everyone could just have\nwhich is access to their creative engines, their souls, their inner fire that comes into the world through craft\nand charging $70 for a drawing lesson feels so exploitative. and I can't tell if it feels exploitative because it is, or because I am just so fucking neurotic and a codependent people pleaser who is afraid of responsibility \n\nor maybe it is exploitative, just not as much as a ceo exploits, but my neurosis makes me extra attentive to it, it triggers feelings in me\n\nbecause the fear pops up in so many places\nit pops up about advertising and marketing my teaching, it pops up in the teaching itself\n\nlets see what my other writing says about it"},
		{"id":"0bf206bccece9be8","x":-210,"y":246,"width":670,"height":1134,"type":"text","text":"telling someone about my workshop that is $70, is assuming that what i have to offer is worth more to them than $70 worth of food, and when we live under such precarity, how can i possibly justify that? something that literally sustains life?\n\nbut i cant know that. for some people what i offer is not worth $70 to them, which is to say, it isn't worth trading 7 hours of work for, which is to say, it isn't worth trading a day's worth of feeding a family for. \nbut for some people it is, because they have a surplus of some kind. those are the people who, unfortunately under our system, have the ability to search for ways to improve their lived experience, able to access the creative parts of themselves and have the resources to let their creative engines run and influence their choices and decisions. the freedom to channel that creative energy. the freedom to live fully, which is to say, to express themselves. and money under capitalism is what allows for expression.\n\ncause look i needed to make advertising videos about my workshop on the 28th, but my true feelings about the workshop are these, its these fears, these ethical blocks\n\nconsidering everything going on in the world, what on earth is the point of drawing right now? i should be protesting. i should be organizing. i should be this, that, whatever\nand even this entire thing im doing right now is fucked by an undercurrent of the knowledge that this IS marketing. it is advertisement and it feels like a scam. even that im scamming myself. that this isn't what i should be doing.\n\nbut also its what i have always wanted to do. and this shit doesnt seem like it's going to end anytime soon. so what do i do, just stop making art and teaching art until its over? it may never be over; and even some of the greatest minds of socialism made art. in fact it could be argued that what they did in organizing was an extension of their creative practices. i mean marxism predates the word creativity even. even creativity is a product of a capitalist system. wtf do we do?\n\nwell, its ok to appropriate and claim words, as long as attempting to do so doesnt inadvertently empower the thing we are trying to disempower and delegitimize. i dont think creativity does this. It is a good word that allows us to conceptualize the use of our intelligence to come up with new ideas and synthesize ideas and concepts together. it refers to a process that existed already, an engine that already existed, that has always existed, potentially, ever since we as humans gained language, probably. when did humans become creative? which is to say, when did we become able to act on our curiosity?\n\n\n\nnone of this is under my own control. all i can do is make the offer known. my fear is that\n\nmaybe i ought to speak about this as a stream of conscious, and then edit it down later?\n\n\nhey yall! my name is danielle, and im teachign a portrait drawing w2orkshop for pride, and im struggling.\n\nfirst, i dont even know if its ethical in the current state of the world to charge for art education. especially when i have the belief that what we need more of in the world is art education, of art appreciation, of seeing beauty in the world, in ourselves, of learning to see the beauty around us. but seeing the beauty around is is terrifying. it raises the stakes, in a way. \n\nsee the world around you crumbling? it's actually beautiful, too. sorry. and it's going away. \n\nbut we need to know the truth. that creation is not something we can let fall apart because we are part of it. I know you feel it. wherever you are, wherever you live. you know in the depths of you that things aren't as beautiful as they used to be. that exploitation is inherently ugly. that your ethics are aesthetics. that violence and hate is ugly, that you're correct that the world is becoming less beautiful, and you're right to feel some type of way about that. \n\nand paradoxically, part of that is doing the sometimes frightening work of seeing things truly, as they are, both ugly and beautiful. an ethics of aesthetics requires us to see past the filters of ideology or of socially constructed myths, to see people for as beautiful as they actually are.\n\nit can be frightening because realizing what is beautiful is also to realize what is being taken from us. it is to realize what is being destroyed by this constant search for profit maximization, of greed by unimaginably wealthy aristocrats who don't give a fuck about their fellow humans. \n\nwe also are called to appreciate the life thats being taken away from us. minute by minute the beauty in our world is being destroyed for profit and that makes seeing the beauty in what is left even more bittersweet. it's not necessarily a comforting feeling.\n\nand not only that, we are torn away from this melting, dripping planet to focus on screens. but i dont want this to be a screed against technology. i dont even feel it like that. but what I do know is that the race to the bottom that was driven by capitalism that devours forests and nations is also the same devouring that is happening to our attention. \n\nyou know how they always say \"if you're not paying, you're the product?\"\n\nyour inner life, your consciousness itself is being colonized for profit. the machine cannot continue to expand endlessly geographically, so it has expanded mentally and begun to privatize and colonize the mind. \n\n\n\n\n\nits also important to note that trying to bring creation back to peoples lives is myself trying to bring creation back to my life as well. in fact, that may be the entire slefish motive behind all of this.\n\n"}
	],
	"edges":[]
}